00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:22.820
and to realize that collisions
can narrow lines and not

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:25.530
just broaden them.

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:27.910
This is sort of
subtle and insightful.

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:31.470
And similar to photon
transitions, it's short,

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:35.300
but I hope it's also a
highlight, because there's

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:39.770
so many people-- you and other
people-- who are sometimes

00:02:39.770 --> 00:02:43.140
struggling-- a photon is
absorbed and is emitted.

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:44.710
Usually, the photon
is not absorbed,

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:46.090
the photon is scattered.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:49.280
And whenever you think
about photon in, photon out,

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:51.810
you really should think
about two-photon transitions.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:54.280
So the framework of
two-photon transitions

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:59.050
allows me now to give you the
tools how you should really

00:02:59.050 --> 00:03:02.869
think about whenever you have
atoms interacting with light.

00:03:02.869 --> 00:03:05.160
The light is not absorbed,
the light is just scattered.

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:06.480
And so you need that.

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:10.350
On the other hand, based
on all the descriptions

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:12.700
I've given you about
light-atom interaction,

00:03:12.700 --> 00:03:14.120
two-photon
transitions would just

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:16.610
mean we need one more order
of perturbation theory,

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:19.060
and then it's the same thing
you have already learned.

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:22.850
So it's a highlight, and it's
to some extent also a review.

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:25.990
You will actually recognize, in
some situations, the difference

00:03:25.990 --> 00:03:28.720
between two-photon processes
and one-photon processes.

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:31.990
It's not so big, it's just
you have to-- you'll see.

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.150
You have to use a
different Rabi frequency

00:03:34.150 --> 00:03:36.930
and some different concepts.

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:37.780
OK.

00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:41.880
So that's, I think, really
an agenda of highlights.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:48.120
Let's go back to the physical
picture we drew up on Wednesday

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.780
about Dicke narrowing.

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:53.310
I just explained
to you that when

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:57.900
we have an atom which is
trapped and tightly confined,

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:03.470
that the spectrum consists of
a sharp light and sidebands.

00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:05.660
And now I was addressing
the situation--

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:07.370
what happens if you
have an atom which

00:04:07.370 --> 00:04:09.520
is surrounded by buffer gas?

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.270
I would say, well, that's a
cheap trap created by nature,

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:16.350
because when the particle
wants to fly away,

00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:18.390
it collides with
a buffer gas atom.

00:04:18.390 --> 00:04:20.490
So it stays put.

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:23.790
So it's a cheap trap, but
it's also a lousy trap,

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:27.070
because there is some randomness
in the number of collisions.

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:29.910
But I'm waving my
arm, so that maybe you

00:04:29.910 --> 00:04:34.050
can go along with the picture
that it is an ensemble of traps

00:04:34.050 --> 00:04:36.620
which have very different
trap frequencies.

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:39.280
And then we would expect,
based on our understanding

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:41.860
of the spectrum of
confined particles,

00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:44.190
that we have a carrier,
which is always the same,

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:47.600
at the electronic
excitation frequency.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:51.130
But then we have sidebands
at the trap frequency.

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:53.450
But those sidebands
are now smeared out,

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:56.010
because we do not have a
defined harmonic oscillator

00:04:56.010 --> 00:04:57.520
potential here.

00:04:57.520 --> 00:05:03.040
So therefore, I sort of
tried to lead you in the way

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:07.340
that that may be one way how you
can think about the situation.

00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:10.950
And well, now I want to give you
a different way to look at it.

00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:14.110
And let's see how those
things come together.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:26.260
So if I would ask you, give
me a quantitative estimate

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:29.444
how wide this line
is, do you have

00:05:29.444 --> 00:05:30.610
any idea how we can do that?

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:38.284
Or let me even put it this way.

00:05:38.284 --> 00:05:39.950
It's again one of
those kind of things--

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:43.080
you have the knowledge, but
to put it together is hard.

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.370
But I would guarantee
everybody in this room

00:05:45.370 --> 00:05:49.897
has the knowledge to write
down in one line what

00:05:49.897 --> 00:05:50.980
is the width of this line.

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:03.630
What is the width of this line?

00:06:03.630 --> 00:06:04.980
It's an inverse time.

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:05.690
What time?

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:10.970
Coherence time.

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:11.690
Yeah.

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:16.190
But now, if you have an
atom which is now starting

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:19.010
and it hits buffer
gas, how would you

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:22.970
estimate the coherence time?

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:24.750
AUDIENCE: Mean free pass.

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:29.070
PROFESSOR: Mean free
pass will be important.

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:30.860
But the coherence
time-- how long

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:34.065
will the atom talk to the laser
beam in a phase-coherent way?

00:06:36.469 --> 00:06:38.510
So what do we have to
compare to the wavelengths?

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:39.310
AUDIENCE: Mean free pass.

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:40.750
PROFESSOR: The mean free pass.

00:06:40.750 --> 00:06:42.422
This will be the
important parameter.

00:06:42.422 --> 00:06:44.130
But if the mean free
pass is much shorter

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:47.100
than the wavelengths?

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:51.310
Well, the atom has just
moved a tiny bit, one mean.

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:53.115
Is it still coherent
at this time?

00:06:53.115 --> 00:06:54.656
AUDIENCE: It's
shorter than the wave.

00:06:54.656 --> 00:06:57.120
PROFESSOR: If the mean free
path is shorter than the wave.

00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:59.230
So it will do many collisions.

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:04.790
But since it stays localized, it
will still coherently interact.

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:08.502
When will it stop
coherently interacting?

00:07:08.502 --> 00:07:09.870
AUDIENCE: Mean free path.

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:12.036
PROFESSOR: No, the mean
free path is always smaller.

00:07:12.036 --> 00:07:14.420
Let's just assume that.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:15.330
I hear "diffusion."

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:17.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:18.930
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:07:18.930 --> 00:07:21.235
The atom has a short
mean free path,

00:07:21.235 --> 00:07:23.500
but it will do a random walk.

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:28.430
And the movement it diffuses
by more than a wavelength,

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:34.630
it has randomly changed its
position by a wavelength.

00:07:34.630 --> 00:07:36.670
And that would
mean it experiences

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:39.190
the phase of the drive
field in a random way.

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:40.690
End of coherence.

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:44.801
1 over this time
is its line width.

00:07:44.801 --> 00:07:45.300
OK.

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:48.140
So let me write that down.

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:52.980
So based on the
concepts we have learned

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.450
by looking at Doppler
broadening and all that,

00:07:55.450 --> 00:07:57.920
we realize the
important aspect is,

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:03.490
when do atoms in an ensemble
randomly move by a wavelength?

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:10.140
So therefore, our
estimate is now--

00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:20.451
estimate the widths
of the sharp peak.

00:08:20.451 --> 00:08:22.720
We use a model
which is diffusion.

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:30.110
We know that in diffusion,
the random walk, the RMS

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:33.650
position in atom has moved away.

00:08:33.650 --> 00:08:36.370
Ballistic motion
is linear in time.

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:39.330
Diffusive motion is the
square root of time,

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:41.720
or z square is linear in time.

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:43.230
And we have the
diffusion constant.

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:53.030
Diffusion by, well,
lambda or lambda

00:08:53.030 --> 00:08:59.055
bar after time, which
is wavelength squared.

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:10.615
So therefore, we would
expect that the full width

00:09:10.615 --> 00:09:20.000
at 1/2 maximum of our peak
is k squared-- k, the wave

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.905
vector of the light, and D
is the diffusion constant.

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:43.720
Well, since you mentioned
the mean free path, let me,

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:46.930
already at this point-- I
wanted to do it earlier,

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:48.550
but it fits in very well here.

00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:56.610
In an ideal gas, the
diffusion constant

00:09:56.610 --> 00:10:04.050
is given by some thermal average
speed times the mean free path.

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:06.920
And if you look
up some textbooks,

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:08.160
there's a factor of 3.

00:10:13.690 --> 00:10:21.260
So our delta omega,
which is k squared

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:27.800
D. Let me write it
as k times v bar.

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:35.160
And the other k I write
as 1 over lambda bar.

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:38.460
So this is k squared,
and I need l.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:41.564
So this is nothing
else than k squared--

00:10:41.564 --> 00:10:44.540
I take this expression,
k squared l.

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:46.540
This is one k, this
is the other k.

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:51.650
And v bar times l is
the ideal gas expression

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:54.700
for the diffusion constant.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:11:00.700
But now you realize that k, dot,
v-- since in a gas, the most

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:03.790
probably velocity is
also the momentum spread,

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:06.980
this is nothing else
than the Doppler width.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:16.750
So therefore, we find
that the line widths

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.840
in Dicke narrowing--
if we have buffer gas

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:28.450
and we have diffusive
motion-- is much smaller--

00:11:28.450 --> 00:11:31.370
and this is why it's
called Dicke narrowing--

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:37.690
than the Doppler broadening
if the mean free path is

00:11:37.690 --> 00:11:40.970
much smaller than
the wavelength.

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:44.900
So this is where the
mean free path comes in.

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:47.630
What happens if
the mean free path

00:11:47.630 --> 00:11:49.703
is much longer than
the wavelength?

00:11:54.740 --> 00:11:57.120
What line widths do we then get?

00:12:02.676 --> 00:12:04.390
Do we then have a
line width which

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:05.973
is larger than the
Doppler broadening,

00:12:05.973 --> 00:12:08.720
or do we get the
Doppler broadening?

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:11.690
Let's have a clicker question.

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:19.070
So if l is much smaller
than lambda bar,

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:28.580
is delta omega-- and this
is your option A-- equal to?

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:34.210
Or option B, larger?

00:12:43.294 --> 00:12:43.794
OK.

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:54.570
So what do you think?

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:56.890
It's always a question
when we derive something,

00:12:56.890 --> 00:12:59.940
how seriously you should
take what we derived.

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:04.330
So this expression
for delta omega Dicke

00:13:04.330 --> 00:13:06.930
shows that the line width
would get larger and larger

00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:10.360
the longer the
mean free path is.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:13.037
And the question is,
is that correct or not?

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:23.410
OK.

00:13:23.410 --> 00:13:26.016
Any more takers?

00:13:26.016 --> 00:13:27.120
Whoops.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:27.620
Oops.

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:28.411
Sorry, press again.

00:13:28.411 --> 00:13:31.250
I erased it by clicking
the wrong button.

00:13:31.250 --> 00:13:33.090
You've already
made up your mind.

00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:35.510
You know the answer.

00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:39.340
So stop, display.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:41.950
Yes.

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:43.700
The majority answer
is definitely correct.

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:47.820
What happens until the
first collision happens,

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:49.790
you just have
normal Doppler-- you

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:52.390
don't have diffusive motion,
you have ballistic motion.

00:13:52.390 --> 00:13:56.240
And if the line width is already
determined once the atoms have

00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:59.150
spread out by a wavelength,
that's it already.

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:02.150
And then if then the particles
collide, it doesn't matter.

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:04.810
So what we have assumed
is we've assumed

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:07.600
that the relevant model for
the spread out to a wavelength

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:08.580
is a diffusive model.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:11.810
And if we are past that--
because the mean free path is

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:13.310
larger than the
wavelength-- we have

00:14:13.310 --> 00:14:15.150
to go back to normal
Doppler broadening.

00:14:17.470 --> 00:14:17.970
OK.

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:26.970
But now let me calculate
Dicke narrowing

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:35.500
by using the formalism
we have developed.

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:38.210
So let's use the correlation
function for that.

00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:47.850
And we know that the line
width was nothing else

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:51.500
than the Fourier transform
of the correlation function,

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:54.670
how the atoms
experience the drive

00:14:54.670 --> 00:14:58.470
field at two different times.

00:14:58.470 --> 00:15:00.800
So we had here the
matrix element,

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:03.990
the Rabi frequency squared.

00:15:03.990 --> 00:15:10.730
We have between time
t and t plus tau,

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:13.480
the phase of the drive
field accumulates

00:15:13.480 --> 00:15:15.850
e to the i omega tau.

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:22.560
But now we have the e
to the minus ikr factor.

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:26.250
And r, or the position--
in diffusion, you

00:15:26.250 --> 00:15:30.360
often call it s-- changes now,
because the particle undergoes

00:15:30.360 --> 00:15:32.000
a random walk.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.960
So what we have to do is to
describe collisional narrowing,

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:39.520
we have to take this
factor and average it

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:45.080
over our ensemble of
diffusing particles.

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:49.650
And well, diffusion means that
if particles start out at t

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:53.940
equals 0 at the
origin, the probability

00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:57.410
that we find the
particle at time t,

00:15:57.410 --> 00:16:01.690
a distance s away
from the origin--

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:04.300
so I'm depicting this one here.

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:06.760
The particle does
sort of a random walk.

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:11.840
And after time t, it
is out at a position s.

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:18.400
And the probability for
that is e to the minus

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:22.920
s squared over 4 Dt.

00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:26.100
And you see it's s
is quadratic over t.

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:28.840
This is a random walk. s
increases s's square root

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:30.540
of time.

00:16:30.540 --> 00:16:35.895
And the probability is
normalized by this expression.

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:49.320
So therefore, this red average
in the correlation function

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:56.720
is calculated by convoluting
with this probability

00:16:56.720 --> 00:16:58.710
distribution for
