00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:15.500
the fluorescent
spectrum of an atom.

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:27.310
As I pointed out in my overview,
we teach much more about it

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:28.205
in 8.422.

00:27:28.205 --> 00:27:30.280
We use a dressed atom picture.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:34.400
But something would be missing
if I wouldn't do it also

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:38.120
in this course, because
we have discussed

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:41.400
to quite some extent what
happens when we excite atoms

00:27:41.400 --> 00:27:43.970
with light.

00:27:43.970 --> 00:27:47.380
And what we have
discussed so far

00:27:47.380 --> 00:28:00.220
is that we excite atom and scan
the laser, or the excitation

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:01.840
frequency.

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:16.240
And when we are plotting the
intensity of the fluorescence,

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:20.040
we are looking at the
number of scattered photon.

00:28:20.040 --> 00:28:24.900
And what we are scanning is
the detuning of the laser.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:36.310
We would expect, in the case
of a motionless atom, simply

00:28:36.310 --> 00:28:41.500
a Lorentzian, or in
the general limit,

00:28:41.500 --> 00:28:43.240
a power-broadened Lorentzian.

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:51.090
Just to be clear, what I'm
discussing in those 10 minutes

00:28:51.090 --> 00:28:54.950
is I'm completely ignoring
that the atom can move.

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:56.450
So you should think
that it's either

00:28:56.450 --> 00:29:00.350
an atom with infinite mass,
or it's an atom tightly

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:02.360
localized in the
Lamb-Dicke limit,

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:07.660
and all we are looking at is the
structure of the central peak.

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:08.820
So no motional effects.

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:12.550
We just look at the pure
kind of intrinsic line

00:29:12.550 --> 00:29:16.245
widths of the
electronic transition.

00:29:16.245 --> 00:29:16.890
OK.

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:18.500
So we have discussed that.

00:29:18.500 --> 00:29:26.940
But now I want to look at
another aspect of spectroscopy.

00:29:26.940 --> 00:29:30.290
And this is another
scan we can do.

00:29:30.290 --> 00:29:33.160
We want to have
a fixed detuning.

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:47.490
And we look at the spectrum
of the emitted light.

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:56.890
So let's assume that
we have a laser which

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:59.590
is at a detuning delta.

00:29:59.590 --> 00:30:01.700
The laser is fixed.

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:03.720
The light is emitting.

00:30:03.720 --> 00:30:07.070
But we are now dispersing
with a spectrograph.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:10.600
We are analyzing what is the
frequency of the emitted light.

00:30:10.600 --> 00:30:12.090
And we determine the spectrum.

00:30:14.800 --> 00:30:19.340
And yes, the question is,
how does it look like?

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:21.680
And I want to give
you four options.

00:30:31.010 --> 00:30:37.040
So this is 0 detuning
at resonance.

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:38.010
Oops, I need one more.

00:30:43.290 --> 00:30:45.600
Let me relabel it
to make it clear.

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:56.840
So our option one
is our spectrum

00:30:56.840 --> 00:31:01.440
is a delta function at
the resonance of the atom.

00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:16.010
Option two is it is a Lorentzian
centered around the resonance.

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:31.370
Option three is it is a
delta function at the laser

00:31:31.370 --> 00:31:33.110
frequency.

00:31:33.110 --> 00:31:44.700
And option four is it is a
Lorentzian with line width

00:31:44.700 --> 00:31:46.380
gamma.

00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:48.130
So we have two options.

00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:51.750
Is it a delta function
at omega 0 or omega l?

00:31:51.750 --> 00:31:54.700
Or is it a Lorentzian-broadened
function at either omega 0

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:57.050
or omega l.

00:31:57.050 --> 00:32:02.760
And since we want to
keep things simple,

00:32:02.760 --> 00:32:08.030
we want to first discuss the
case of the perturbative case

00:32:08.030 --> 00:32:12.990
that the laser which excites
the atom has very low power.

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:14.370
So what would you expect?

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:17.040
An atom is excited, it's
a little light bulb.

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:19.890
You analyze the spectrum
of the light bulb.

00:32:19.890 --> 00:32:22.720
Which of the four
spectrum will you measure?

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:07.320
OK.

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:08.320
Let's try again.

00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:11.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:11.470 --> 00:33:15.510
And maybe I should, like
our online learning system,

00:33:15.510 --> 00:33:17.770
try to give you one hint.

00:33:17.770 --> 00:33:22.620
I want you to really think hard
what energy conservation means

00:33:22.620 --> 00:33:23.330
in this problem.

00:33:46.741 --> 00:33:47.240
OK.

00:33:53.530 --> 00:33:55.890
OK, we're getting closer.

00:33:55.890 --> 00:33:58.640
Now, the way how I want
you to think about it

00:33:58.640 --> 00:34:04.030
is if you take the
limit of low power,

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:06.450
you should really think
about it that there

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:09.210
is only one photon in
your whole laboratory.

00:34:09.210 --> 00:34:11.260
This photon is
scattered of an atom,

00:34:11.260 --> 00:34:14.380
and then you measure the
frequency of the photon.

00:34:14.380 --> 00:34:20.030
And energy conservation clearly
tells us that the frequency

00:34:20.030 --> 00:34:23.820
of the scattered photon cannot
be at the resonance frequency.

00:34:23.820 --> 00:34:25.880
It has to be at the
laser frequency.

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:29.310
Otherwise, we would
violate energy.

00:34:29.310 --> 00:34:31.600
But it seems-- still,
the more subtle thing

00:34:31.600 --> 00:34:34.850
is, is it a delta function?

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:39.016
Of course, a delta
function will be broadened.

00:34:39.016 --> 00:34:41.320
If you do the experiment
for one second,

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:44.239
you will have a Fourier
line width which is 1 hertz.

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:46.590
But that's, for
practical reasons, almost

00:34:46.590 --> 00:34:49.580
like a delta function, because
the spectral line widths,

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:51.884
or the natural line widths
of your favorite atom

00:34:51.884 --> 00:34:53.699
is 10 megahertz.

00:34:53.699 --> 00:34:55.989
So there will be some
temporal broadening,

00:34:55.989 --> 00:34:58.810
which is in case in any
realistic experiment.

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:01.660
But we are talking about, are
you limited by the experiment

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:03.580
and by technical
noise, or are you

00:35:03.580 --> 00:35:06.610
limited by the
natural line widths?

00:35:06.610 --> 00:35:09.341
Now, I would argue, just
with energy conservation--

00:35:09.341 --> 00:35:11.340
but I'll give you another
argument in a second--

00:35:11.340 --> 00:35:13.560
that if I have a
monochromatic laser,

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:15.140
the photon which
has to come out has

00:35:15.140 --> 00:35:17.370
to be exactly the
same frequency.

00:35:17.370 --> 00:35:20.360
Because we talked about
energy conservation.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:23.500
And if I would start with a
photon at the laser frequency

00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:27.630
and I would measure a photon
which has 10 megahertz away,

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:32.310
I would violate energy
conservation by 10 megahertz.

00:35:32.310 --> 00:35:34.490
So the argument is
actually correct.

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:41.390
It's a delta function
at the drive frequency.

00:35:41.390 --> 00:35:45.730
But I want to give
you another argument.

00:35:45.730 --> 00:35:48.600
It's, again, something you
have heard in the course.

00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:50.400
But you should really
take it seriously,

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:52.080
and apply to that situation.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:53.290
And that's the following.

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:56.480
Remember when we talked
about the AC stark effect.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:35:58.940
I told you that
you should really

00:35:58.940 --> 00:36:04.240
think about the atom as
a harmonic oscillator.

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:07.380
We even introduced for you
the oscillator strengths

00:36:07.380 --> 00:36:10.560
that we could even
quantitatively describe

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:16.110
the response of the atom
to the scattering of light

00:36:16.110 --> 00:36:18.800
by pretty much a model where we
have a mechanical model where

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:22.680
an electron is attached
with a spring to an origin.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:24.717
OK.

