oscillator not at omega 0;

00:36:52.850 --> 00:36:55.780
we were driving it at
a frequency omega l.

00:36:59.321 --> 00:37:03.280
At what frequency does the
harmonic oscillator respond?

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:06.502
At the drive frequency
or at its own frequency?

00:37:06.502 --> 00:37:07.386
AUDIENCE: Drive.

00:37:07.386 --> 00:37:08.290
PROFESSOR: Of course.

00:37:08.290 --> 00:37:10.300
It's a drive frequency.

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:13.920
And if you have a CW experiment,
I said let's wait a second,

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:17.600
let's really do a
long experiment,

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:19.440
if you have a driven
harmonic oscillator,

00:37:19.440 --> 00:37:21.560
and you drive it
for a long time,

00:37:21.560 --> 00:37:26.090
and you analyze the
spectrum of the motion,

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:30.300
is the frequency spectrum of
the driven harmonic oscillator

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:32.920
absolutely sharp at
the drive frequency?

00:37:32.920 --> 00:37:35.885
Or is it broadened by
gamma, the damping constant

00:37:35.885 --> 00:37:37.010
of the harmonic oscillator?

00:37:40.589 --> 00:37:41.563
AUDIENCE: Sharp.

00:37:44.485 --> 00:37:46.506
PROFESSOR: Who
thinks it's sharp?

00:37:46.506 --> 00:37:49.380
Who thinks it's broad?

00:37:49.380 --> 00:37:51.200
Hands up for sharp.

00:37:51.200 --> 00:37:53.699
Hands up for broad.

00:37:53.699 --> 00:37:54.199
OK.

00:37:54.199 --> 00:37:55.185
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:55.185 --> 00:37:58.870
PROFESSOR: Look, what you are
overlooking is the following.

00:37:58.870 --> 00:38:01.220
There is the difference
between a transient, which

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:03.390
is damped out at a rate gamma.

00:38:03.390 --> 00:38:06.000
But then there is
the CW response.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:10.230
If you have an ultra-weak drive,
you leave it on for an hour,

00:38:10.230 --> 00:38:12.730
the harmonic oscillator
will reach steady state.

00:38:12.730 --> 00:38:15.910
And it will just oscillate
driven by your drive.

00:38:15.910 --> 00:38:18.070
And it's actually monochromatic.

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:20.010
And if you analyze
the motion, it's

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:22.890
a harmonic oscillator in
steady state with a drive,

00:38:22.890 --> 00:38:26.480
and it just moves with a fixed
amplitude and fixed frequency.

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:29.580
I mean, the way how
I shake my hands,

00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:33.730
this is a delta function
at the drive frequency.

00:38:33.730 --> 00:38:36.780
So in this simple
harmonic oscillator model,

00:38:36.780 --> 00:38:40.410
gamma and damping
comes in when you

00:38:40.410 --> 00:38:47.890
do what I discussed
earlier, when

00:38:47.890 --> 00:38:49.890
you change the drive frequency.

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:52.356
But this is a completely
different experiment.

00:38:52.356 --> 00:38:53.980
We are not changing
the drive frequency

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:55.680
and looking for the response.

00:38:55.680 --> 00:38:58.136
We are a fixed drive
frequency, and we

00:38:58.136 --> 00:39:01.750
are analyzing what the
motion is which comes out.

00:39:01.750 --> 00:39:04.660
And then, as you know from
differential equation,

00:39:04.660 --> 00:39:06.500
you may have a grade transient.

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:08.930
You may have a transient
at the resonance frequency

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:12.750
which dies out
with a rate gamma.

00:39:12.750 --> 00:39:14.970
This is when you suddenly
switch on your drive,

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:17.310
and you're not adiabatically
switching on your drive.

00:39:17.310 --> 00:39:19.130
But this is just a transient.

00:39:19.130 --> 00:39:21.910
But what we are asking here
when you do a CW experiment,

00:39:21.910 --> 00:39:25.400
you drive it for a long
time, you look what happens.

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:31.970
And the motion of the
driven harmonic oscillator

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:35.580
is a delta function
at the drive.

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:37.970
And what is valid for
a harmonic oscillator

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:39.930
is also valid for
the atom, pretty much

00:39:39.930 --> 00:39:40.805
for the same reasons.

00:39:44.960 --> 00:39:45.635
Any questions?

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:49.740
Yes.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:51.781
AUDIENCE: Regarding the
energy conservation in D,

00:39:51.781 --> 00:39:56.418
wouldn't the photon processes
explain energy conservation?

00:39:56.418 --> 00:39:57.540
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:39:57.540 --> 00:39:59.240
You are now really
asking-- Nancy

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:02.060
is asking about
two-photon processes.

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:03.660
Well, we don't
want to stop here.

00:40:03.660 --> 00:40:05.689
We want to see something
more interesting.

00:40:05.689 --> 00:40:07.730
This is just sort of the
trivial, simple harmonic

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:08.610
oscillator.

00:40:08.610 --> 00:40:13.862
The question is now, if you
want to see something richer,

00:40:13.862 --> 00:40:15.950
if we want to see a
little bit of broadening,

00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:18.650
or we want to see something
which is not as boring as just

00:40:18.650 --> 00:40:22.204
a classical harmonic oscillator,
what do we have to do?

00:40:22.204 --> 00:40:24.464
AUDIENCE: Increase the strength.

00:40:24.464 --> 00:40:27.260
PROFESSOR: Increase the
strengths of the field.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:30.502
And I heard somebody
saying, two photons.

00:40:30.502 --> 00:40:31.210
And that may be--

00:40:31.210 --> 00:40:31.780
AUDIENCE: Next-order
perturbation theory.

00:40:31.780 --> 00:40:32.720
PROFESSOR: Pardon?

00:40:32.720 --> 00:40:33.660
AUDIENCE: It's like next
order perturbation theory.

00:40:33.660 --> 00:40:35.660
PROFESSOR: Next-order
perturbation theory.

00:40:35.660 --> 00:40:37.770
But just in the sort
of intuitive picture,

00:40:37.770 --> 00:40:41.020
if you have two photons
which come quickly enough--

00:40:41.020 --> 00:40:44.370
and how quickly the two
photons come will be debated.

00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:46.685
Of course, it's parametrized
by the Rabi frequency,

00:40:46.685 --> 00:40:47.980
the strengths of the drive.

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:50.859
But if two photons come
quickly, each photon

00:40:50.859 --> 00:40:52.900
has to be scattered with
a delta function because

00:40:52.900 --> 00:40:54.300
of energy conservation.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:56.910
But if we have two
photons, suddenly, it's

00:40:56.910 --> 00:40:59.920
possible that one is scattered
here and one is scattered here.

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:01.760
And we still conserve energy.

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.480
So if you want to see some form
of line broadening, if you want

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:08.870
to see all the things
you have mentioned,

00:41:08.870 --> 00:41:11.250
we have to go away from
the low power limit.

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:18.650
And this is what we do next.

00:41:22.250 --> 00:41:26.730
So we assume that we
have higher power.

00:41:29.316 --> 00:41:30.260
We are on resonance.

00:41:35.560 --> 00:41:45.130
And let me assume that the Rabi
frequency is larger than gamma.

00:41:49.020 --> 00:41:51.309
So what is the physics now
of the atom if the Rabi

00:41:51.309 --> 00:41:52.600
frequency is larger than gamma?

00:41:56.530 --> 00:41:59.570
It can do Rabi oscillation
before it's damped.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:04.420
So now we have a
system which has

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:07.025
an internal dynamics
at the Rabi frequency.

00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:12.780
And you know if you
have an emitter,

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:15.150
if you have an antenna
which emits light,

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:18.870
and you move the antenna
around at a frequency--

00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:21.680
we had the example of a trapped
particle which has a trapped

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:25.230
frequency of omega
trap-- the spectrum,

00:42:25.230 --> 00:42:29.450
if you Fourier transform, it
leads to the basal function,

00:42:29.450 --> 00:42:31.520
it leads to the sideband.

00:42:31.520 --> 00:42:35.820
So therefore, we know now,
based on all the analogies,

00:42:35.820 --> 00:42:38.310
if you have a modulated
emitter, we obtain sidebands.

00:42:43.210 --> 00:42:46.310
That's what we would
expect classically.

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:49.490
So let me now ask you the
three following possibilities.

00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:55.410
Maybe we still get
a delta function.

00:42:55.410 --> 00:43:01.400
Maybe we get three peaks where
the splitting is the Rabi

00:43:01.400 --> 00:43:02.950
frequency.

00:43:02.950 --> 00:43:12.660
So the two outer
peaks have a-- and the

00:43:12.660 --> 00:43:17.810
third option is that yes, we
observe the Rabi frequency,

00:43:17.810 --> 00:43:20.740
but the Rabi frequency
is the splitting

00:43:20.740 --> 00:43:21.910
between the outer peaks.

00:43:26.350 --> 00:43:30.650
So the first and second
answer differ by a factor of 2

00:43:30.650 --> 00:43:32.005
in the sideband spacing.

00:43:35.730 --> 00:43:37.150
So we have three choices.

00:43:37.150 --> 00:43:38.750
Do we expect sidebands?

00:43:38.750 --> 00:43:42.890
That's A and B. Or would
you expect that we still

00:43:42.890 --> 00:43:45.589
have a delta function,
because, well, maybe energy has

00:43:45.589 --> 00:43:47.380
to be conserved at the
single photon level?

00:43:51.070 --> 00:43:55.880
And then is the splitting
Rabi frequency on each side,

00:43:55.880 --> 00:43:59.020
or Rabi frequency between
the two sidebands?

00:44:13.012 --> 00:44:13.512
All right.

00:44:18.410 --> 00:44:19.640
Yes.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:23.030
It's indeed the situation.

00:44:23.030 --> 00:44:27.280
For those who picked
A, it's pretty much

00:44:27.280 --> 00:44:29.155
the definition of what
the Rabi frequency is.

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:38.300
After one cycle of
the Rabi frequency,

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:41.040
the atom has gone
from the ground state

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:44.390
to the excited state and
back to the ground state.

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:48.520
So the model you should have is
that you have an object which

00:44:48.520 --> 00:44:50.050
is emitting light,
but the object

00:44:50.050 --> 00:44:53.980
has some internal modulation
at the Rabi frequency.

00:44:53.980 --> 00:44:58.260
Whatever factor of 2
you had in the amplitude

00:44:58.260 --> 00:45:00.540
versus probability or
something, all this

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:02.620
has been factored into
the definition of the Rabi

00:45:02.620 --> 00:45:05.680
frequency in such a way
the atom is really blinking

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:08.230
between ground and excited
state with a frequency

00:45:08.230 --> 00:45:09.970
which is the Rabi frequency.

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:14.020
And this frequency
leads-- and the spectrum

00:45:14.020 --> 00:45:20.600
is now the sum and difference
of the relevant frequencies.

00:45:20.600 --> 00:45:24.850
And the relevant frequency
is the resonance frequency

00:45:24.850 --> 00:45:26.780
and the Rabi frequency.

00:45:26.780 --> 00:45:28.980
So the answer is B.

00:45:28.980 --> 00:45:33.880
But this was sort of more
in form of a stick diagram.

00:45:33.880 --> 00:45:38.140
Now I want to bring in
in the next question

00:45:38.140 --> 00:45:40.280
the line broadening.

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:47.950
So the question is-- and
there are again four choices.

00:45:47.950 --> 00:45:52.905
The question is, we have
now our three sticks.

00:45:55.610 --> 00:45:59.660
One is a carrier, and these
are the two sidebands split off

00:45:59.660 --> 00:46:02.470
by a Rabi frequency.

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:06.140
Are all three sticks now
sharp delta functions?

00:46:10.450 --> 00:46:13.490
Are all three sticks broadened
by the natural line widths?

00:46:17.240 --> 00:46:20.470
Is the central part
sharp, and only the

00:46:20.470 --> 00:46:22.850
sidebands are broadened?

00:46:22.850 --> 00:46:28.102
Or do we have a sharp
stick with a pedestal,

00:46:28.102 --> 00:46:29.060
and then two sidebands?

00:46:31.810 --> 00:46:34.960
I'm not actually expecting
all of you to know the answer,

00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:37.160
because this is
really now getting

00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:38.380
into more subtle things.

00:46:38.380 --> 00:46:42.680
But just in terms
of show-and-tell,

00:46:42.680 --> 00:46:46.040
and attract your curiosity
to the second part

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:49.140
of the course, what
would you expect?

00:47:20.045 --> 00:47:20.545
OK.

00:47:25.580 --> 00:47:26.130
Yes.

00:47:26.130 --> 00:47:26.960
Good.

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:31.150
A is definitely eliminated.

00:47:31.150 --> 00:47:34.430
I mean, if we scatter two
photons simultaneously, there

00:47:34.430 --> 00:47:38.090
will be sort of
broadening of gamma,

00:47:38.090 --> 00:47:39.840
because the atom has
a natural broadening.

00:47:39.840 --> 00:47:43.940
So we can't expect that the
two photon processes are sharp.

00:47:43.940 --> 00:47:45.330
There's no reason
to expect that.

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:57.120
The answer between B,
C, and D depends now.

00:47:57.120 --> 00:48:00.820
If we have very, very little
power, what we observe

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:04.200
is, of course, the
low-power delta function.

00:48:04.200 --> 00:48:07.470
And then we observe very,
very small sidebands

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:10.070
which are broadened.

00:48:10.070 --> 00:48:12.200
So answer C is correct.

00:48:12.200 --> 00:48:14.370
If you just think
about it-- what

00:48:14.370 --> 00:48:16.820
is the structure of
infinitesimal peaks?

00:48:16.820 --> 00:48:20.290
But when you crank up the
power, and what you have is

00:48:20.290 --> 00:48:22.200
you have an elastic
scattering peak,

00:48:22.200 --> 00:48:24.530
which has a delta function,
energy conservation

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:26.180
at the single photon level.

00:48:26.180 --> 00:48:30.280
And then you have those-- they
are called inelastic peaks.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:35.030
But when you crank up the
power, then the central feature

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:38.150
has also an inelastic component.

00:48:38.150 --> 00:48:41.115
You can sort of argue
that in Rabi oscillation,

00:48:41.115 --> 00:48:43.490
you are in the ground state,
excited state, ground state,

00:48:43.490 --> 00:48:44.210
excited state.

00:48:44.210 --> 00:48:46.960
But if you do now light
scattering in the excited

00:48:46.960 --> 00:48:49.230
state, you
automatically broaden it

00:48:49.230 --> 00:48:52.380
by the lifetime of
the excited state.

00:48:52.380 --> 00:48:55.870
And if you crank up the
power higher and higher,

00:48:55.870 --> 00:48:59.050
the elastic peak will be
more and more suppressed.

00:48:59.050 --> 00:49:01.210
And you find actually
a spectrum which

00:49:01.210 --> 00:49:03.695
has only three broadened
peaks, and the delta function

00:49:03.695 --> 00:49:05.860
has disappeared.

00:49:05.860 --> 00:49:10.380
It will actually be something
where we need more knowledge.

00:49:10.380 --> 00:49:14.030
The broadening of those
peaks is not gamma anymore.

00:49:14.030 --> 00:49:16.410
One of them will be 3/2
gamma, the other one

00:49:16.410 --> 00:49:18.720
will be 1/2 gamma.

00:49:18.720 --> 00:49:22.820
But this now really requires
a deeper understanding

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:24.860
in terms of the atom picture.

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:27.100
But the scale of
all the broadening

00:49:27.100 --> 00:49:31.700
is a factor on the order
of unity times gamma.

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:32.500
Any questions?

00:49:39.210 --> 00:49:43.670
So the general answer, sorry,
would be-- the generic picture

00:49:43.670 --> 00:49:46.080
which you should keep
in your mind is that.

00:49:46.080 --> 00:49:50.010
You have inelastic scattering
on all three peaks.

00:49:50.010 --> 00:49:55.060
But the limit of D at
very low power is that.

00:49:55.060 --> 00:50:01.655
And at very high power, is that.

00:50:01.655 --> 00:50:04.710
The elastic component
of the central peak

00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:06.290
is either 100% or 0%.

00:50:16.510 --> 00:50:17.010
OK.

00:50:33.580 --> 00:50:45.670
So our last topic for line
shapes and line broadening

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:48.270
is pressure broadening.

00:50:48.270 --> 00:50:50.890
And as I mentioned
in the introduction,

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:54.600
pressure broadening has
made modern appearances

00:50:54.600 --> 00:50:58.290
in the form of clock shift,
and mean field shifts,

00:50:58.290 --> 00:51:02.450
and mean field broadenings
in Bose-Einstein condensates.

00:51:02.450 --> 00:51:05.360
But let me sort of
tell you how you

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:07.260
should understand
pressure broadening.

00:51:10.110 --> 00:51:14.590
I'm using here the
semi-classical picture

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:19.155
that an excited atom
acts as an oscillator.

00:51:23.210 --> 00:51:29.660
And what happened is the atom--
you can say the oscillation

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:32.990
is superposition of
ground and excited state.

00:51:32.990 --> 00:51:35.150
It oscillates.

00:51:35.150 --> 00:51:46.920
But after some time tau, there
may be a quenching collision,

00:51:46.920 --> 00:51:48.280
a de-excitation collision.

00:51:52.030 --> 00:51:55.950
Then the atom is sort
of in the ground state.

00:51:55.950 --> 00:51:59.130
And then it waits until it's
excited again by the laser,

00:51:59.130 --> 00:52:03.540
and the atomic dipole
is oscillating again.

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:05.840
In a situation like
this, you would

00:52:05.840 --> 00:52:11.730
expect that the total
line widths is actually

00:52:11.730 --> 00:52:13.450
the sum of two rates.

00:52:13.450 --> 00:52:17.100
One is the spontaneous
emission rate,

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:23.520
and the other one would be the
collision rate, which is this.

00:52:28.710 --> 00:52:33.660
And in general, this is sort
of how people looked at it.

00:52:33.660 --> 00:52:37.250
You vary the pressure
in your buffer gas cell,

00:52:37.250 --> 00:52:40.490
and you find that the line
width has a component which

00:52:40.490 --> 00:52:42.520
increases linearly
with pressure.

00:52:45.900 --> 00:52:49.390
So this is one model
how you can imagine

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:51.470
what happens in a collision.

00:52:51.470 --> 00:52:54.470
These are like
knock-out collisions.

00:52:54.470 --> 00:52:57.730
When an atom collides,
the excitation, the energy

00:52:57.730 --> 00:52:58.460
disappears.

00:52:58.460 --> 00:53:01.940
The atom is quenched
to the ground state.

00:53:01.940 --> 00:53:05.770
Well, we can draw
up another model,

00:53:05.770 --> 00:53:14.310
where we have an oscillation
of our atomic oscillator.

00:53:14.310 --> 00:53:23.240
But then after
the same time tau,

00:53:23.240 --> 00:53:26.100
there is now a
hiccup in the phase.

00:53:26.100 --> 00:53:28.290
It collides with another atom.

00:53:28.290 --> 00:53:30.750
The other atom is
not de-exciting.

00:53:30.750 --> 00:53:32.550
It's not removing the energy.

00:53:32.550 --> 00:53:34.910
But after the
collision, the atom

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:40.440
continues to oscillate, but with
a very, very different phase.

00:53:40.440 --> 00:53:44.780
And sort of what I assumed
here is this time where

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:48.540
the collision happens
is very short.

00:53:48.540 --> 00:53:51.480
It's a very short
collision time.

00:53:51.480 --> 00:53:54.850
That I can approximate
the collisions

00:53:54.850 --> 00:53:59.540
as simply imparting random
phase jumps to the atom.

00:54:02.440 --> 00:54:05.240
Well, if you ask,
what is the widths

00:54:05.240 --> 00:54:09.830
of the spectroscopic line,
it's exactly the same result.

00:54:12.350 --> 00:54:14.710
It just means we have
a different rate.

00:54:14.710 --> 00:54:18.420
It's now a de-phasing
rate, which is 1 over tau.

00:54:18.420 --> 00:54:20.370
And this is added to the
spectroscopic widths.

00:54:26.830 --> 00:54:27.850
OK.

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:33.340
This is sort of just creating
some phenomenological picture.

00:54:33.340 --> 00:54:37.116
Let's now ask a little
bit more microscopically.

00:54:39.630 --> 00:54:40.683
How can it happen?

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:53.250
How can it happen that there
is a phase change, that there's

00:54:53.250 --> 00:54:57.910
a change in the phase of
the atomic oscillator?

00:54:57.910 --> 00:55:02.470
And this leads us now to
consider the interaction

00:55:02.470 --> 00:55:08.680
potential as a function
of r between two atoms.

00:55:08.680 --> 00:55:14.240
We have one atom which is
sort of our active atom, which

00:55:14.240 --> 00:55:18.110
has an excited and ground state.

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:21.475
And this atom is now
getting closer to,

00:55:21.475 --> 00:55:24.840
let's say, an argon atom,
which acts as buffer gas.

00:55:24.840 --> 00:55:27.450
And what I'm plotting
in this graph now

00:55:27.450 --> 00:55:32.830
is the interaction potential
between our light-emitting,

00:55:32.830 --> 00:55:35.970
or light-absorbing, atoms
and the buffer gas atom.

00:55:35.970 --> 00:55:38.090
And let's just
genetically assume there

00:55:38.090 --> 00:55:40.140
is sort of something like
a molecular potential.

00:55:44.220 --> 00:55:48.840
But in general, the
molecular potentials

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:51.070
will be different in the
ground and excited state.

00:55:53.750 --> 00:55:56.850
And of course, if you
do hyperfine transitions

00:55:56.850 --> 00:55:58.750
between atoms in a
Bose-Einstein condensate,

00:55:58.750 --> 00:56:00.200
you may have a
scattering length,

00:56:00.200 --> 00:56:02.170
which is different
in the two states.

00:56:02.170 --> 00:56:04.010
And I think you
see the connection.

00:56:04.010 --> 00:56:07.364
So in general, if the
interaction environment

00:56:07.364 --> 00:56:09.280
is different between
ground and excited state,

00:56:09.280 --> 00:56:11.210
we expect that the
interaction potential

00:56:11.210 --> 00:56:13.670
causes certain shifts.

00:56:13.670 --> 00:56:27.860
So we could use the picture
that we have a phase evolution.

00:56:27.860 --> 00:56:30.910
And the phase evolution
is a frequency difference

00:56:30.910 --> 00:56:35.580
which is simply given by
the difference of the two

00:56:35.580 --> 00:56:38.440
potentials.

00:56:38.440 --> 00:56:40.650
So the picture is a little
bit-- which is actually

00:56:40.650 --> 00:56:43.530
very valid for cold
collisions, which-- well,

00:56:43.530 --> 00:56:45.580
really a new chapter
in atomic physics

00:56:45.580 --> 00:56:49.260
opened up by laser cooling
and magneto-optic traps.

00:56:49.260 --> 00:56:51.570
An atom, when it emits a
photon, would emit here

00:56:51.570 --> 00:56:53.290
at the resonance frequency.

00:56:53.290 --> 00:56:56.170
But if the collision
is very, very slow,

00:56:56.170 --> 00:56:59.990
it will actually emit,
with a certain probability,

00:56:59.990 --> 00:57:04.130
a photon which is shifted
by exactly this expression.

00:57:04.130 --> 00:57:07.200
And in that limit, that
could be very interesting,

00:57:07.200 --> 00:57:08.760
because by analyzing
the spectrum

00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:10.780
of the immediate light,
you learn something

00:57:10.780 --> 00:57:12.655
about the interaction
potential of two atoms.

00:57:15.530 --> 00:57:24.330
But of course, this argument
has a little bit of a flaw,

00:57:24.330 --> 00:57:29.493
because you can observe a
frequency not instantaneously.

00:57:37.335 --> 00:57:55.060
You can observe-- if a
collision happens very fast,

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:59.690
you would actually go through
those frequency changes so fast

00:57:59.690 --> 00:58:01.120
that you cannot resolve them.

00:58:01.120 --> 00:58:04.160
The question is,
which one is larger?

00:58:04.160 --> 00:58:10.290
So if the frequency
shift is larger

00:58:10.290 --> 00:58:16.250
than the inverse time for the
duration of the collision,

00:58:16.250 --> 00:58:17.250
then you can observe it.

00:58:17.250 --> 00:58:19.180
Otherwise, you can't.

00:58:19.180 --> 00:58:22.420
So the picture we should
draw is now the following.

00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:24.230
And this is sort of
a microscopic picture

00:58:24.230 --> 00:58:27.070
on those phase jumps,
which I mentioned earlier.

00:58:27.070 --> 00:58:29.280
That you have your
atomic oscillator.

00:58:29.280 --> 00:58:30.860
The atom is oscillating.

00:58:30.860 --> 00:58:33.400
But now it comes
close to another atom.

00:58:33.400 --> 00:58:37.260
And let's assume there
is an energy increase

00:58:37.260 --> 00:58:39.630
between ground and excited
state due to the presence

00:58:39.630 --> 00:58:40.970
of the buffer gas atom.

00:58:40.970 --> 00:58:44.180
Then you would say you
get a quick oscillation.

00:58:44.180 --> 00:58:46.340
Depending on the
impact parameter,

00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:49.980
it can last various
amount of time.

00:58:49.980 --> 00:58:52.230
And then later, the
oscillation starts.

00:58:52.230 --> 00:58:55.485
But essentially, this
causes a random phase jump.

00:59:00.710 --> 00:59:03.380
So this time here is the
collision time tau c.

00:59:19.820 --> 00:59:34.030
What we expect now is we
have to now interpolate

00:59:34.030 --> 00:59:36.080
between two models.

00:59:36.080 --> 00:59:39.360
I'm not taking it any
further than that.

00:59:39.360 --> 00:59:44.130
We have an interesting
line shape.

00:59:44.130 --> 00:59:48.880
There may be a central part
which is simply collisionally

00:59:48.880 --> 00:59:54.780
broadened by the
interruptions of the phase,

00:59:54.780 --> 00:59:57.980
by the number of collisions
with the collision time tau.

01:00:03.310 --> 01:00:12.040
But if when the atoms collide,
there is a huge frequency shift

01:00:12.040 --> 01:00:19.230
momentarily, that this will
actually affect the wings.

01:00:19.230 --> 01:00:23.540
So for frequency shifts which
come from the interaction

01:00:23.540 --> 01:00:29.840
potential which are much
larger than the collision time,

01:00:29.840 --> 01:00:34.560
than the time
between collisions,

01:00:34.560 --> 01:00:38.260
we will observe
something which goes

01:00:38.260 --> 01:00:42.580
by the name "far
wing broadening."

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:46.580
And also, the central part
of the potential is simply,

01:00:46.580 --> 01:00:50.647
you can say, it's a
Lorentzian which is simply

01:00:50.647 --> 01:00:51.980
broadened by the collision rate.

01:00:51.980 --> 01:00:54.160
There is no microscopic
information--

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:56.070
what is the nature,
what is going on

01:00:56.070 --> 01:00:57.660
during the phase jumps.

01:00:57.660 --> 01:01:00.634
The wings will have
actually information

01:01:00.634 --> 01:01:01.883
about the molecular potential.

01:01:15.710 --> 01:01:18.680
And I just wanted to present
it to you in this way

01:01:18.680 --> 01:01:21.480
to sort of show how you
actually have, in a line shape,

01:01:21.480 --> 01:01:22.980
often two effects.

01:01:22.980 --> 01:01:25.850
One is pretty much
just the interruption

01:01:25.850 --> 01:01:28.990
of the coherence which
gives the central line.

01:01:28.990 --> 01:01:32.070
But you still have, at
least in some limit,

01:01:32.070 --> 01:01:36.100
information about what
causes those phase jumps.

01:01:36.100 --> 01:01:39.770
And this appears in the wings.

01:01:39.770 --> 01:01:42.440
20 years ago in the
atomic physics course,

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:45.550
we taught you a theory
how to describe that.

01:01:45.550 --> 01:01:47.990
It could be probably
taught in one hour.

01:01:47.990 --> 01:01:49.750
There are some
links on the Wiki,

01:01:49.750 --> 01:01:52.780
but I don't want to
carry that further.

01:01:52.780 --> 01:01:55.114
Any questions about that?

01:01:55.114 --> 01:01:57.030
AUDIENCE: So why has the
importance decreased?

01:02:05.191 --> 01:02:07.020
PROFESSOR: The
importance has decreased

01:02:07.020 --> 01:02:08.965
of that, because
I mean, who of you

01:02:08.965 --> 01:02:12.280
is studying atoms and gas cells?

01:02:12.280 --> 01:02:13.380
Nobody.

01:02:13.380 --> 01:02:15.030
The frontier has moved on.

01:02:15.030 --> 01:02:17.300
We are much more in a
regime where we are not

01:02:17.300 --> 01:02:19.940
observing atoms in
certain environment.

01:02:19.940 --> 01:02:23.510
We are creating an interesting
system out of atoms

01:02:23.510 --> 01:02:26.445
by putting the atoms in a
well-defined environment where

01:02:26.445 --> 01:02:28.940
those things are absent.

01:02:28.940 --> 01:02:31.820
Or in the ultra-cold
domain, and de Broglie

01:02:31.820 --> 01:02:36.270
wavelengths is so long that this
kind of model for collisions

01:02:36.270 --> 01:02:38.000
is no longer applicable.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:41.250
We are in the extreme case of
a single partial wave, where

01:02:41.250 --> 01:02:43.320
a single parameter,
the scattering lengths,

01:02:43.320 --> 01:02:44.840
describes all of it.

01:02:49.111 --> 01:02:49.610
OK.

01:02:59.355 --> 01:02:59.855
Cory?

01:02:59.855 --> 01:03:00.648
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:03:00.648 --> 01:03:03.038
Could you talk for a
little bit about how

01:03:03.038 --> 01:03:05.428
this model of collisions
breaks down and allows

01:03:05.428 --> 01:03:08.236
for Dicke narrowing?

01:03:08.236 --> 01:03:09.610
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:03:09.610 --> 01:03:10.310
Thank you.

01:03:10.310 --> 01:03:12.660
That was one comment I forgot.

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:17.360
What happens is you have Dicke--
thanks for this question.

01:03:17.360 --> 01:03:21.370
You have Dicke-- I drew up
the two potential curves.

01:03:21.370 --> 01:03:25.310
If the two potential curves
are absolutely identical,

01:03:25.310 --> 01:03:28.812
the atoms can approach
each other and can collide.

01:03:28.812 --> 01:03:30.270
But there is never
any perturbation

01:03:30.270 --> 01:03:33.270
to the atomic oscillator,
because the frequency

01:03:33.270 --> 01:03:36.480
between ground and
excited state is omega 0,

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:39.682
no matter whether the atom
undergoes a collision or not.

01:03:39.682 --> 01:03:46.140
In this limit, which is
often realized in collisions

01:03:46.140 --> 01:03:48.550
with rare gases,
in this limit, you

01:03:48.550 --> 01:03:52.140
do not have any phase
interruption by the collision.

01:03:52.140 --> 01:03:54.490
And this is the prerequisite
for Dicke narrowing.

01:03:59.170 --> 01:03:59.670
OK.

01:03:59.670 --> 01:04:02.070
I think we have the
full picture now.

01:04:02.070 --> 01:04:05.915
And that means we can move
on to two-photon excitations.

01:04:13.080 --> 01:04:15.600
So whenever you
start a new chapter,

01:04:15.600 --> 01:04:17.050
you should motivate it.

01:04:17.050 --> 01:04:21.270
And the question is, why
should you be interested?

01:04:21.270 --> 01:04:24.270
Well, I can also turn it
around and said, why not?

01:04:24.270 --> 01:04:26.250
Because those things happen.

01:04:26.250 --> 01:04:29.430
And if those things happen,
we want to learn about them.

01:04:29.430 --> 01:04:32.060
And they actually
happen very naturally.

01:04:32.060 --> 01:04:34.960
The moment you go to
higher laser power

01:04:34.960 --> 01:04:37.820
and you go beyond the lowest
order of perturbation theory,

01:04:37.820 --> 01:04:41.730
you may actually excite two
photons at the same time.

01:04:41.730 --> 01:04:44.060
And actually, what we just
discussed about the emission

01:04:44.060 --> 01:04:48.150
spectrum of an atom, with the
sidebands, with the broadening,

01:04:48.150 --> 01:04:51.080
these are actually
examples where we really

01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:54.000
have to think about it in
a two-photon picture, not

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:55.050
a single-photon picture.

01:05:00.886 --> 01:05:05.240
The second motivation
is very practical.

01:05:05.240 --> 01:05:09.770
We may want to excite an
atom from a low-lying level

01:05:09.770 --> 01:05:11.180
to a high-lying level.

01:05:11.180 --> 01:05:14.700
But the only laser we can
buy, or the only laser we have

01:05:14.700 --> 01:05:17.600
in the laboratory
has lower frequency.

01:05:17.600 --> 01:05:19.190
That doesn't mean
that the case is

01:05:19.190 --> 01:05:22.890
lost by just stacking two
photons on top of each other.

01:05:22.890 --> 01:05:25.340
We can bridge the
gap and still excite

01:05:25.340 --> 01:05:28.580
the atom, which has
transitions only far in the UV.

01:05:28.580 --> 01:05:30.390
And all we have is
these visible lasers.

01:05:32.970 --> 01:05:35.680
There's another
thing which changes.

01:05:35.680 --> 01:05:40.850
Maybe we want to excite hydrogen
from the 1s to the 2s level.

01:05:40.850 --> 01:05:43.230
1s and 2s have the same parity.

01:05:43.230 --> 01:05:46.260
And if we try to excite
it with one photon,

01:05:46.260 --> 01:05:50.040
because of the dipole
operator which has odd parity,

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:51.960
this is not allowed.

01:05:51.960 --> 01:05:54.040
So there are maybe
selection rules

01:05:54.040 --> 01:05:57.250
where we can go to
desirable final state

01:05:57.250 --> 01:06:00.790
only with two photons
and not with one photon.

01:06:12.730 --> 01:06:21.990
Finally, I will show you
on Wednesday-- remember,

01:06:21.990 --> 01:06:25.630
there is no class on Monday,
because the whole CUA

01:06:25.630 --> 01:06:29.610
will go crazy with the NSF
site visit on Monday, Tuesday.

01:06:29.610 --> 01:06:31.216
So the next class on Wednesday.

01:06:31.216 --> 01:06:32.590
And on Wednesday,
I will actually

01:06:32.590 --> 01:06:38.030
show you if the two photons come
from counter-propagating beams,

01:06:38.030 --> 01:06:41.020
the net momentum transfer
to the atom is 0.

01:06:41.020 --> 01:06:45.050
And net momentum transfer of
0 means zero Doppler shift.

01:06:45.050 --> 01:06:48.470
So two photons give
us an opportunity,

01:06:48.470 --> 01:06:50.860
which doesn't exist
with the single photon.

01:06:50.860 --> 01:06:53.445
We can excite the atom
without transferring momentum.

01:06:56.220 --> 01:07:00.190
And this is the basis of a
Doppler free spectroscopy

01:07:00.190 --> 01:07:02.240
technique.

01:07:02.240 --> 01:07:05.350
And finally, for purely
conceptional reasons,

01:07:05.350 --> 01:07:08.140
we've talked so much about
excitation of an atom,

01:07:08.140 --> 01:07:11.410
and then ask, what is the
rate of light scattering?

01:07:11.410 --> 01:07:15.630
So we have actually used
two-photon processes

01:07:15.630 --> 01:07:18.606
in the course many, many
times without actually

01:07:18.606 --> 01:07:19.730
adequately addressing them.

01:07:23.865 --> 01:07:25.240
I didn't tell you
anything wrong.

01:07:25.240 --> 01:07:27.050
I was sort of choosing
my words carefully,

01:07:27.050 --> 01:07:29.840
that everything I told you about
light emission and absorption

01:07:29.840 --> 01:07:32.520
is comparable with
the correct picture.

01:07:32.520 --> 01:07:35.140
And the correct picture
is if a photon goes in

01:07:35.140 --> 01:07:37.650
and a photon goes out,
you have to describe it

01:07:37.650 --> 01:07:41.050
as one process
involving two photons.

01:07:41.050 --> 01:07:43.840
So I think we have
enough reasons why

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:47.790
we should be interested.

01:07:47.790 --> 01:07:54.200
And if I take this picture,
that I start in one state

01:07:54.200 --> 01:08:06.720
and have a two-photon
absorption process,

01:08:06.720 --> 01:08:13.110
I actually want to
redraw it, because

01:08:13.110 --> 01:08:17.560
in the dipole approximation,
which I want to use here,

01:08:17.560 --> 01:08:23.979
we have the dipole operator,
and second quantization

01:08:23.979 --> 01:08:25.490
is a plus a dagger.

01:08:25.490 --> 01:08:28.090
The electric field
is a plus a dagger.

01:08:28.090 --> 01:08:31.090
So each application
of the operator

01:08:31.090 --> 01:08:35.560
takes us from one state to
the next with a single photon.

01:08:35.560 --> 01:08:40.430
So therefore, if you
talk about two photons,

01:08:40.430 --> 01:08:48.870
we can only absorb
them if we have

01:08:48.870 --> 01:08:54.050
an intermediate state,
which I will call f.

01:08:54.050 --> 01:08:58.640
So we should really think
about two-photon absorption

01:08:58.640 --> 01:09:07.261
as a two-step process which
involves an intermediate state.

01:09:11.500 --> 01:09:13.510
And it has to be
like that if we want

01:09:13.510 --> 01:09:16.100
to use, as the
operator for atom light

01:09:16.100 --> 01:09:18.470
interaction, the
dipole operator,

01:09:18.470 --> 01:09:21.000
because a dipole
operator is creating

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:23.620
and-- the dipole operator
involves electric field.

01:09:23.620 --> 01:09:27.850
And that creates or annihilates
one photon at a time.

01:09:27.850 --> 01:09:29.819
Let me just make a
side remark, but this

01:09:29.819 --> 01:09:32.229
will be addressed in 8.422.

01:09:32.229 --> 01:09:35.330
If you use the description
of the interaction

01:09:35.330 --> 01:09:37.189
with the electromagnetic
field, which

01:09:37.189 --> 01:09:44.260
is the p minus e Hamiltonian,
and you square it,

01:09:44.260 --> 01:09:48.240
if you square that, you
get an A squared term.

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:51.550
The A squared term is
actually the product

01:09:51.550 --> 01:09:54.580
of a plus a dagger squared.

01:09:54.580 --> 01:09:56.980
So you can actually,
with the A squared term,

01:09:56.980 --> 01:10:02.740
scatter two photons by going
from one state to another one.

01:10:02.740 --> 01:10:06.060
But I'm not discussing it here.

01:10:06.060 --> 01:10:10.690
And I leave a detailed
comparison and discussion

01:10:10.690 --> 01:10:13.120
of that to 8.422.

01:10:13.120 --> 01:10:16.030
Now we are strictly adhering
to the dipole approximation.

01:10:16.030 --> 01:10:17.940
Oh, actually, let me
make a comment about it,

01:10:17.940 --> 01:10:22.220
because I just realized if I
say something and don't say it

01:10:22.220 --> 01:10:24.080
fully, I may confuse people.

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:27.730
So what I want to say is,
we will show, in 8.422

01:10:27.730 --> 01:10:31.350
that the two pictures, the
pap minus a Hamiltonian

01:10:31.350 --> 01:10:35.780
and the dipole Hamiltonian
are equivalent.

01:10:35.780 --> 01:10:39.670
They're connected by
canonical transformation.

01:10:39.670 --> 01:10:43.720
So therefore, it is not a
fundamental aspect of nature,

01:10:43.720 --> 01:10:45.920
whether you can scatter
only one photon when

01:10:45.920 --> 01:10:48.140
you go from one
state to the other.

01:10:48.140 --> 01:10:50.200
There are two
equivalent descriptions.

01:10:50.200 --> 01:10:52.790
In one description, you
sometimes scatter two photons.

01:10:52.790 --> 01:10:55.330
In the other description,
you scatter only one photon.

01:10:55.330 --> 01:10:57.830
And you will all
get a PSET in 8.422

01:10:57.830 --> 01:11:00.860
where you show for one
example that the results are

01:11:00.860 --> 01:11:04.500
the same when you sum up
over all possibilities.

01:11:04.500 --> 01:11:06.790
So therefore, I can
maybe here should rather

01:11:06.790 --> 01:11:11.400
take the position, the generic
description of light scattering

01:11:11.400 --> 01:11:13.440
uses the dipole approximation.

01:11:13.440 --> 01:11:16.170
And in the dipole
approximation, we

01:11:16.170 --> 01:11:18.860
are describing the
atoms, that they only

01:11:18.860 --> 01:11:22.510
exchange one photon when they
go from one state to the next.

01:11:22.510 --> 01:11:26.190
And this is a full description
but not the only description.

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:33.020
So therefore, we need
an intermediate state.

01:11:33.020 --> 01:11:36.170
But assuming that the
first laser is not

01:11:36.170 --> 01:11:39.420
resonant with the transition
to the intermediate state,

01:11:39.420 --> 01:11:42.000
we need this dashed line.

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:46.820
This dashed line is sometimes
called a virtual state.

01:11:46.820 --> 01:11:49.485
And in the following
discussion, we

01:11:49.485 --> 01:11:52.570
will really learn what is the
nature of the virtual state

01:11:52.570 --> 01:11:54.750
and what does it mean.

